Explanation:\
SETUP causes randomly dispersed red turtles to be created in the world. The number of red turtles created is controlled by the population slider.\
When the GO button is clicked, the red turtles start wiggling around randomly as they produce a green substance. The substance is not created by all red turtles; in fact, only a certain amount of turtles produce it (this is observed by changing the population number- more substance is produced when there are more turtles and less substance is produced when there are less turtles).\
\
The substance is represented by green patches- some red turtles turn the patch they are currently on to the color green when the GO forever button is on. When other red turtles come into contact with these green-patch turtles, they also start coloring their patches green. The ability to produce the green substance spreads from turtle to turtle, and as the turtles move around, patches temporarily become green.\
\
What\'92s interesting is that the substance-producing turtles somehow detect each other and move towards each other. They aggregate into large groups of substance-producing turtles. When a substance-producing turtles is surrounded by other substance-producing turtles on neighboring patches, it\'92s substance color (AKA patch color) changes from green to white. The result is multiple groups of red turtles with white patches.\
\
How accurate is my breakdown of the mechanics?\
My explanation was mostly accurate- the red turtles are slime cells which produce a chemical called cyclic AMP. The chemical works in waves (meaning it spreads from cell to cell) and causes them to aggregate into a group in order to work as a single, larger organism. They are able to detect each other from a certain distance, after they have a certain amount of chemical. From here, they move towards each other and form a huge entity of slime mold cells. \
\
My only misconception was that I thought the substance color changed from green to white immediately, when in reality, the substance simply turned lighter shades of green after coming into contact with other turtles. \
